Once you clone a remote repo to your local machine, 
the first thing you may want do is: Customize your git.
What in your git, can you customize and configure?
To see what you already have:
# git config --list

But you dont know where these configs are made.
What their scope is -- Do these config apply to:
	- The entire system for all users? (Least priority)
		[path]/etc/gitconfig
	- Only to the user's repos? (Can override system-wide config)
		~/.gitconfig OR ~/.config/git/config
	- Only to this repo? (Can override user-level and system-level config)
		.git/config
You get the answer with:
# git config --list --show-origin
(See output of this command at the bottom of this file)

You can edit/set a few config items, with one of the 3 scopes with:
To change system-wide config, you can edit that config file.
git config --replace-all --local core.editor "C:\\Program\ Files\\Notepad++\\notepad++.exe" # User level
git config --local user.name yrnr # --local is default


C:\Users\myusername\Git-ProGit>git config --list --show-origin
